# How to start Machine Learning with Uber Ludwig

Imagine if Machine Learning required no PhD in Computer Science. Imagine if somebody without any special AI knowledge could put an AI into any kind of application without any hassle. There is a solution for that. Let's see.

I do Machine Learning research in Bioinformatics and work as a Machine Learning Developer in industry. I have used ludwig both in research and industrial tasks and it is very well suited for lightning speed prototyping and testing simple hypotheses. Ludwig is a perfect first step in solving your Machine Learning task, before you try implementing something complicated in Pytorch or Tensorflow. Chances are, you won't need anything else.

Basically, Uber Ludwig is like CreateML but based.

It has

1. No fancy graphical interface - use command line, script in python or go away
2. No restrictions like "you can use only fancy apple hardware"

It is marketed as "no-code ML" but ***IN IMPERIAL RUSSIA*** "no-code" means "not cool enough". We'll do that the proper way, with a lot of python. So, let's go.

What I'll do is simple: I'll make a solution for a Kaggle problem with ludwig to show the basic steps. You can use this example as a guideline to use Ludwig and there is a good probability you wouldn't need any other material but this notebook and Ludwig official documentation.

Let's make a Jupyter notebook and import stuff that we need. We'll need numpy, pandas, os module - the usual stuff for data analysis and communicating with file system. Next we'll import from ludwig.api LudwigModel class and from ludwig we'll import logging because we want to see the progress.

```python
import os
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

from ludwig import logging
from ludwig.api import LudwigModel
```

Now let's go to kaggle and get our dataset downloaded. Our task is Mechanisms of Action prediction. Key idea in this competition (which ended four month ago) is to guesstimate the way how a certain drug works from the results of some biological experiments. That explanation is good enough for today, you can check out the paper for the dataset by following the link in the description.

We have the following files in the dataset. We won't use train_drug.csv and train_targets_nonscored, so we're left with:

`train_features.csv` - Features for the training set. Features `g-` signify gene expression data, and `c-` signify cell viability data. `cp_type` indicates samples treated with a compound (`cp_vehicle`) or with a control perturbation (`ctrl_vehicle`); control perturbations have no MoAs; `cp_time` and `cp_dose` indicate treatment duration (24, 48, 72 hours) and dose (high or low).

`train_targets_scored.csv` - The binary MoA targets that are scored. `test_features.csv` - Features for the test data. You must predict the probability of each scored MoA for each row in the test data. `sample_submission.csv` - A submission file in the correct format.

Let's load the train and test data and see the data with our eyes (always useful). So we have 876 columns in our data dataset and tens of thousands of rows. A lot of tabular data.

```python
train_features = pd.read_csv("train_features.csv", index_col=0)
test_features =  pd.read_csv("test_features.csv", index_col=0)
train_targets_scored = pd.read_csv("train_targets_scored.csv", index_col=0)
```

The columns have different types. Ludwig offers a type abstraction to describe the dataset for the model. There are a lot of types (numeric, image, category, binary, text, sound and so on). The types determine what kind of a model would be used, Ludwig offers some state-of-the-art models for image data. Our data though are pretty tabular. We have three categorical types and the rest of columns are numeric. 

So we need to specify the input features. I'll do the final list of input features by looping over the list of columns - there are a bunch of more elegant and efficient ways to do this but I would like to show what happens

```python
input_features = [
    {"name": "cp_type", "type": "binary"},
    {"name": "cp_time", "type": "category"},
    {"name": "cp_dose", "type": "category"},
]
input_features.extend(
    [{"name": a, "type": "numerical"} for a in train_features.columns[3:]]
)
output_features = [{"name": a, "type": "numerical"} for a in train_targets_scored.columns]
```

All of our outputs will be numeric. The task is a classification, but not your usual classification since there could be more than one class assigned to an example.

Let's see how the number of labels is distributed. To do so, we'll sum the train_targets_scored matrix along the column axis. We can already see that some have three labels, some even zero labels and so on.

```python
plt.hist(np.sum(train_targets_scored.values, 1))
```

![img](data:image/png;base64,)

As you can see, from the histogram, most have one label, but there could be as much as seven. Therefore, this task is not a pure classification, but something else. For simplicity, we'll consider it a case of regression.

So our model is defined by specifying the input features and output features. 

```python
model_definition = {
    "input_features": input_features,
    "output_features": output_features
}
model = LudwigModel(model_definition, logging_level=logging.DEBUG)
```

Ludwig in scripts operates on pandas dataframe, which we need to create. I don't remember how to use pd.concat properly, so let's just do the np.concatenate and form the dataframe out of the result. In research, it is ok as long as it works (but do it properly in production ;)

```python
train_df = pd.DataFrame(
    np.concatenate([train_features.values, train_targets_scored], 1)
)
train_df.columns = train_features.columns.tolist() + train_targets_scored.columns.tolist()
```

Training is simple: just run the model.train on train_df and collect the stats. The training could take some time, at the time of writing the post, my laptop 3080 wasn't at speaking terms with tensorflow (but pytorch, my main workhorse was doing fine) so that was computing on the CPU. 

```python
train_stats = model.train(train_df)
```

Ludwig automatically splits the data into train, test and validation, and you can see the performance in the output. Here the loss used is mean squared error, basic loss for the regression problem, and we can see the values for each target variable separately and the total result along with r2, mean absolute error and other stuff. 

Let's wait when it stops. Ludwig also sets the early stopping automatically, and you can change the value in the model definition, basic value is 5 epoch. If we don't see any improvement for 5 passes over the whole training sets, the training stops. That is what early stopping is for ;)

I'll plot the loss vs epochs for training (combined), test and validation.

![img](data:image/png;base64,)

To predict the labels for the data, we'll just call the predict method on the test_features dataframe.

```python
test_predictions = model.predict(test_features)
```

We get some predictions and that is supposed to work somehow, I guess. 

We've covered everything that would help you try machine learning fast with ludwig. Except for one tiny thing...

How to use the model? Imagine that you would like to load the model inside an app. What should you do?

Ludwig automates saving the snapshots of the model and keeps (by default) the best model discarding all the rest. It saves the model in the results folder, making a folder for each experiment.

The experiment folder has three items in it:

1. description.json - the full description of the training. You can get the config out of the config field, and see some metadata (version, random seed etc) in the rest of the fields.
2. training_statistics.json - the history of training for each of the targets, the one we've visualized above.
3. model folder - the weights and other data required to use the model.

We load the model by providing the path to model folder for the load method of the LudwigModel class.

```python
trained = LudwigModel.load("results/api_experiment_run_0/model/")
```

So, that's it!
